FORMULA 1, DIRECT USA GP: TOWARD 2021 AND BEYOND
Yesterday in Austin - where the US Grand Prix will take place on Sunday - the new technical regulation was finally officially presented, which will come into effect in 2021. In a couple of years the Formula 1 cars will change radically with the 'objective to reduce costs and the huge gap that currently separates the top teams from the teams that on the other hand cannot afford to spend crazy sums, through the introduction of the so-called budget cap which obviously is not favorably viewed by Mercedes, Ferrari and Red Bull. The hope (punctually betrayed in the past) is to watch more spectacular races and see fewer "artificial" overtaking on the track built using the DRS. But as long as the cars continue to be unmanageable when they are in the wake of those in front of them, it is unlikely that there will be this change of course. The idea is to eliminate the completely flat bottom in order to contain the aerodynamic load loss. Finally, a reshuffling of the strength values would not be bad, after 6 years of uninterrupted domination of the Silver Arrows: in IndyCar there are teams like Penske, Ganassi and Andretti that dominate the scene but it is not rare to see them elbowing with outsiders hunting for the their moment of glory. Here in Formula 1 it is simply unthinkable to see a Stroll or a Giovinazzo fighting for the victory together with the Hamilton, Verstappen or Leclerc ... {adj. by Stefano Belli}
